In the Singleton Design Pattern, each instance of the class is created exactly once at the time of instantiation. This ensures that no other instances are created until they are explicitly destroyed. The main advantage of this approach is that it provides better encapsulation and reduces coupling between different parts of the application.

To implement the Singleton Pattern correctly, you would typically use the following constructor:

```java
public class Singleton {
    private static volatile Singleton instance;
    private Singleton() {}
}
```

